<paragraph id="8BCC5F1CFFFA2D63FF51F347FC00FDA3" blockId="0.[151,1437,1052,2006]" lastBlockId="1.[151,1436,152,623]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="132" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">
Discussion. The vast diversity of 
<taxonomicName id="4C73249FFFFA2D62FDA9F347FD07F89A" box="[575,695,1855,1878]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Diallactiini">Diallactiini</taxonomicName>
is found in the tropics rather than the temperate regions (Jaschhof 2016), a fact rendering 
<taxonomicName id="4C73249FFFFA2D62FE02F326FDD9F8BA" authorityName="Jaschhof &amp; Ham &amp; Bae" authorityYear="2018" box="[404,617,1886,1910]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Loboplusia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coreana">
<emphasis id="B907830EFFFA2D62FE02F326FDD9F8BA" box="[404,617,1886,1910]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Loboplusia coreana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a remarkable discovery. Even more remarkable is the disjunct geographical distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="4C73249FFFFA2D62FED5F306FE0BF85A" box="[323,443,1918,1942]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Loboplusia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B907830EFFFA2D62FED5F306FE0BF85A" box="[323,443,1918,1942]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Loboplusia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with one species each in the northern Neotropical and the eastern Palearctic region. Considering that the 
<taxonomicName id="4C73249FFFFA2D62FEEDF3E7FE43F87A" box="[379,499,1951,1974]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Diallactiini">Diallactiini</taxonomicName>
are a very ancient lineage (Jaschhof 2016), the present-day occurrence of 
<taxonomicName id="4C73249FFFFA2D62FAB2F3E6FA2CF87A" box="[1316,1436,1950,1974]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Loboplusia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B907830EFFFA2D62FAB2F3E6FA2CF87A" box="[1316,1436,1950,1974]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Loboplusia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
might be relict and reflect a distribution that at some point in the past was conjunct and much more extensive. However, any attempt of interpreting the distributional pattern revealed here has to take the sparse availability of data into account: we simply don’t know yet, for instance, whether the distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="4C73249FFFFB2D63FCEEF4CFFC40FF03" box="[888,1008,183,207]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Loboplusia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B907830EFFFB2D63FCEEF4CFFC40FF03" box="[888,1008,183,207]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="132">Loboplusia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Neotropics is confined to higher altitudes (where basically temperate conditions prevail), or whether other, still uncollected species occur in other parts of the world (as entire regions are practically unexplored for 
<taxonomicName id="4C73249FFFFB2D63FCD3F480FC72FEC3" box="[837,962,248,271]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Diallactiini">Diallactiini</taxonomicName>
). Moreover, it is rather unlikely that the distribution as presently known for both 
<taxonomicName id="4C73249FFFFB2D63FDD0F560FD15FEE3" baseAuthorityName="Jaschhof" baseAuthorityYear="2016" box="[582,677,280,303]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Loboplusia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zurqui">
<emphasis id="B907830EFFFB2D63FDD0F560FD15FEE3" box="[582,677,280,303]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="132">L. zurqui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C73249FFFFB2D63FD4EF560FCFAFEE3" authorityName="Jaschhof &amp; Ham &amp; Bae" authorityYear="2018" box="[728,842,280,303]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Loboplusia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coreana">
<emphasis id="B907830EFFFB2D63FD4EF560FCFAFEE3" box="[728,842,280,303]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="132">L. coreana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
reflect the total areas of these species. We would not be surprised to see that ongoing research reveals a genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C73249FFFFB2D63FC83F54FFC3DFE83" box="[789,909,311,335]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Loboplusia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B907830EFFFB2D63FC83F54FFC3DFE83" box="[789,909,311,335]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="132">Loboplusia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that is more species-rich and has a basically pantropical distribution, with single species managing to adapt to temperate conditions. More data about the diversity and distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="4C73249FFFFB2D63FEF5F500FE6EFE43" box="[355,478,376,399]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Diallactiini">Diallactiini</taxonomicName>
, including 
<taxonomicName id="4C73249FFFFB2D63FDC2F50FFD7CFE43" box="[596,716,375,399]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Loboplusia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B907830EFFFB2D63FDC2F50FFD7CFE43" box="[596,716,375,399]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="132">Loboplusia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, are needed to resolve those issues. With respect to the provenance of 
<taxonomicName id="4C73249FFFFB2D63FF20F5EFFE3CFE63" authorityName="Jaschhof &amp; Ham &amp; Bae" authorityYear="2018" box="[182,396,407,431]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Loboplusia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coreana">
<emphasis id="B907830EFFFB2D63FF20F5EFFE3CFE63" box="[182,396,407,431]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="132">Loboplusia coreana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is worth noting that the fungivorous subfamilies of 
<taxonomicName id="4C73249FFFFB2D63FC77F5E0FB35FE63" box="[993,1157,408,431]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cecidomyiidae</taxonomicName>
, including 
<taxonomicName id="4C73249FFFFB2D63FB69F5E0FA28FE63" authorityName="Panelius" authorityYear="1965" box="[1279,1432,408,431]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Winnertziinae">Winnertziinae</taxonomicName>
, have remained largely unstudied in 
<collectingCountry id="F3641F8CFFFB2D63FD81F5C0FDE8FE03" box="[535,600,440,463]" name="South Korea" pageId="1" pageNumber="132">Korea</collectingCountry>
until very recently; and the discovery described here is a first outcome of our efforts to close this gap of knowledge. Our data, mostly unpublished, suggest that the eastern Palearctic region hosts an extremely rich and diverse fauna of fungus-feeding cecids, including a considerable proportion of supposedly Oriental elements that are absent in the better investigated western Palearctic (e.g., Jaschhof 2000). In other words, for a better understanding of the Palearctic fauna we need to allocate more resources for taxonomic study to the east of the region, where the potential for making exciting discoveries is so patently obvious.
</paragraph>
